        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-03-03 01:14:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/10cd891c-839c-11e2-85c9-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  1 tests failed: conf-sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "7076f4eda09cc894ee56a47bd4455362f8403680",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-04 18:00:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(3 inline comments)\n\nFor example:\nptlrpc_lprocfs_rd_nrs_crrn_quantum -> ptlrpc_nrs_policy_control -> nrs_policy_ctl -> nrs_policy_ctl_locked ->  policy->pol_desc->pd_ops->op_policy_ctl()\n\nIf the code path above is possible before the PTLRPC_NRS_CTL_START command is issued, then we're calling into a module by the op_policy_ctl() pointer without a ref count on that module, since the get_module() is called when handling PTLRPC_NRS_CTL_START. I failed to see why op_policy_start needs to be protected against module removal but op_policy_ctl doesn't need it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "662e58c11823a877e10dc0d368a2174d5d4427b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 130,
        "name": "Nikitas Angelinas",
        "email": "nikitas.angelinas@hpe.com",
        "username": "nikitas_angelinas"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-06 11:44:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (3 inline comments)\n\nThe code path example that Isaac gave is possible, and we would be calling into a module without holding a ref count, but the idea was that since nrs_policy_ctl() and ptlrpc_nrs_policy_unregister->nrs_policy_unregister_locked()->nrs_policy_unregister() are serialized by nrs->nrs_lock, then as long as the user calls ptlrpc_nrs_policy_unregister() in the module's exit() function, this should be a safe operation.\n\nBut I agree that is not a clean solution; I will rework it probably by having some of the struct ptlrpc_nrs_pol_desc fields held internally by NRS within the ptlrpc module, such that they can be accessed safely.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "4a5840ec188f2fa3242cbfd37eb9bdaab2272a3c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 130,
        "name": "Nikitas Angelinas",
        "email": "nikitas.angelinas@hpe.com",
        "username": "nikitas_angelinas"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-06 11:47:09.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "36a07d3545097c4fbb42c990f959d2196a8b36ec",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 130,
        "name": "Nikitas Angelinas",
        "email": "nikitas.angelinas@hpe.com",
        "username": "nikitas_angelinas"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-06 13:41:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nIow, the main idea with this patch was to keep a reference on the module whenever the policy could possibly be handling an RPC, because taking and releasing a reference for each RPC would be unwanted overhead, and it is not how module refcounting is really supposed to work; i.e. ideally there should be one reference from one module to the other. As mentioned in previous comments, I think this patch needs to be reworked so that it does not rely on the user calling ptlrpc_nrs_policy_register() in module->exit(), possibly by copying some struct ptlrpc_nrs_pol_desc fields inside NRS in the ptlrpc module, unless there is a better idea on how the patch should work.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
